Jubilee Party to amend poll laws ahead of election

 The impression that he is untouchable, mostly a 21st Century one, partly arose from the persistent abuse of the word “independence” in the Independent Electoral and boundaries Commission, IEBC. The abuse of the word “independence” was part of generated drama to frustrate IEBC’s work, sometimes through well-orchestrated court injunctions. Besides effort to frustrate the IEBC, there were other political attractions that portended gloom. Party nominations were manufactured disasters as members traded insults inside among themselves and outside directed at rival parties. Officials gave nomination certificates to two different claimants and some ‘losers’ received nomination certificates in some bush rather than in offices.
 After the chaotic nominations, there were exhilarating ups involving exemplary general voter behavior, lining up for hours to vote. While dignitaries and candidates, as expected, tended to get priority to vote without waiting in line, First Lady Margaret Kenyatta defied expectations. She actually has a habit of defying odds and expectations and of setting the global pace for other first ladies. Her marathon feat was unexpected and captured global imagination. She did it again on the voting day. Like other women in her polling station, she patiently and good naturedly lined up for three hours to cast her vote, no privileges. She thus defied the norm for dignitaries and showed good example.
